An explores decoloniality’s conception of the sacred in relation to revolutionary violence, gender, creolization, and racial phenomenology, demonstrating its potential for reshaping religious paradigms. Pointing out that the secular has been pivotal to regulating racial hierarchies under colonialism, he advocates for a broader understanding of religion that captures the fundamental ideas that drive decolonial thinking. By examining how decolonial theory incorporates the sacred into its vision of liberation, An invites readers to rethink the transformative power of decoloniality and religion to build a hopeful future.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aDecolonizationxReligious aspects2DLC. 0aDecolonizationxReligious aspects. 0aHispanic American theology2DLC. 0aHispanic American theology. 0aImperialism2DLC. 0aImperialism. 0aPostcolonial theology2DLC. 0aPostcolonial theology. 0aPostcolonialismxReligious aspectsxChristianity2DLC. 0aPostcolonialismxReligious aspectsxChristianity. 0aRacismxReligious aspectsxChristianity2DLC. 0aRacismxReligious aspectsxChristianity. 0aReligion and politics2DLC. 0aReligion and politics. 0aReligionxPhilosophy2DLC. 0aReligionxPhilosophy. 7aRELIGION / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDuke University Press Complete eBook-Package 2024z978311135689108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023 Englishz978311131929208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023z9783111318912oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Cultural and Area Studies 2023 Englishz978311131909408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Cultural and Area Studies 2023z978311131812740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781478027096?locat